{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"23cfeb13-8a74-49ef-87fb-839eeb693ad4","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Analyze** it in Visual Studio (**File → Open**) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview).\n\n**Alternative — `dotnet-counters`** for a quick live look before tracing:\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If the container image lacks the .NET SDK, you can use `dotnet-trace` from a **sidecar** or enable the [diagnostic port](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/diagnostics-in-containers) via the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` environment variable to connect from the host.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4852da5b-cb85-467a-ae6d-496575ce380c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":437,"requestId":"2C4E:203D52:14C40F6:17715E3:69F94648"},"id":"66a4d519-fcb8-4fa6-ac0e-40c97e37a66c","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:22:25.667Z","parentId":"c9cab504-3c94-4520-8836-659990fe2939"}
